<h2>4. Objects, Attributes, and Methods</h2>

<p>In Ruby, everything is an object. Objects know information, called <em>attributes</em>, and they can do actions, called <em>methods</em>.</p>

<p>For an example of an object, think about you as a human being. You have attributes like height, weight, and eye color. You have methods like &quot;walk&quot;, &quot;run&quot;, &quot;wash dishes&quot;, and &quot;daydream.&quot;  Different kinds of objects have different attributes and methods. In the next sections we&#8217;ll look at a few specific kinds of objects common in Ruby.</p>

<p>A class is an <em>abstract</em> idea, it defines what all objects of that type can know and do. Think of the chair you&#8217;re sitting in. It&#8217;s not an abstract chair, it is an actual chair. We&#8217;d call this actual chair an <em>instance</em> - it is a realization of the idea chair. It has measurable attributes like height, color, weight. The <em>class</em> chair, on the other hand, has an abstract weight, color, and size &#8211; we can&#8217;t determine them ahead of time.</p>

